The world was much warmer in the Eocene (~55-35 mya) than today--especially in polar regions. Sometime around the beginning of the Oligocene (~34 mya), the world cooled and Antarctica glaciated rapidlywith great implications for life. Although there was a general trend of cooling during the Eocene, this Eocene-Oligocene transition was the first big step toward the cooler world of today. We know that a reduction in CO2 was one driver ofglobal cooling, but other mechanisms, including changes in ocean circulation--perhaps due to opening of Southern Ocean Gateways-- have been proposed. Either way, substantial further study was necessary to understand the pattern and timing of Antarcticcooling across the Eocene and transition into the Oligocene. 


This transdisciplinary, multi-institution study brought together paleoclimate modelers, modern oceanographers, paleo-ecologists, and marine geologists to study the co-evolution of life and climate at high latitudes, through the lens of shark teeth. The project integrated and synthesized data and methods from biology, geochemistry, ocean-atmospheric dynamics, and modeling. This combination was innovative and required regular,deep communication between the faculty, post-docs, and students across the programmatic elements. Monthly meetings amongst all the project participants were held and the methods and research modalities of each discipline were introduced to the other teams, which generated meaningful and long lasting impacts for everyone involved. 


Within the Purdue team (led by Huber and including Phd student Adam Aleksinski and Post-doc Xiaoqing Liu) Eocene neodymium ocean circulation proxy records and paleotemperature records (either generated by other project teams, i.e. led by co-PI Sora Kim or Howie Scher or from previous publications) were compiled and georeferenced. The neodymium and isotope enabled version of the NCAR CESM was set up and run both at NCAR and at Purdue under the mentorship of co-PI Alexandra Jahn and with great assistance from NCAR paleoclimate scientist Jiang Zhu. Long integrations of CESM were carried out thatare a good match for middle Eocene conditions as revealed by comparison ofmodelled results with isotopic and circulation proxy records. These simulations needed to be integratedfar longer than expected because the site of deepwater formation changed after thousands of years(even after having initialized with a previous 'equilibrated' simulation). Thisis an interesting result by itself, suggesting either the presence of multi-equilibria or a more general necessity for 4000 year paleoclimate integrations. Sensitivity studiesat a range of CO2 and ocean gateway configurations were carried out that appear to capture the relative changes across the Eocene-Oligocene transition, although some systematic biases in models and proxy data exist, if the proxies representannual mean conditions. 


We now have simulations that clearly delineate the relative roles of CO2 and Drake Passage depth in driving oxygen isotope and neodymium ocean circulation distributionsand the necessary compilations of data to evaluate which of the proposed mechanisms best explains the available data. In terms of intellectual merit, the main outcomes of this set of simulations are:

high CO2 values are necessary to reproduce Eocene warmth and a "correct" ocean circulation;
lowering of CO2 generates relative changes that correspond well to more Oligocene-like conditions overall;
shark teeth that we have analyzed leave wide room for interpretation and are compatible with multiple interpretations;
opening of Drake Passage also clearly changes the east-west gradient of neodymium in just the way that has been previously identified in published records, which indicates that gateway opening is an important part of the neodymium tracer story;
in the model at least, the climatic implications of this are small, suggesting that CO2 is the main driver of the climate change, regardless of what is going on with Southern Ocean circulation.



More broadly, we have also learned the importance of considering the paleo-ecological and behavioral aspects of using sharks as probes of paleo-ocean circulation. This knowledge is potentially transferable to other proxy systems in which vertical movement, migration, and potential for 'niche tracking' may be important. We have attempted to constrain these factors as much as possible in our model-data comparison through careful consideration of these factors among the shark teeth. Further development of these concepts into a full proxy system model will likely bear fruit.


Results of this work have been presented at several international conferences, published in a series of joint publications, and associated proxy data and model output have been archived in publicly available repositories. The work of publishing the latest results is ongoing. In terms of broader impacts, one PhD student will graduate with this as the core of his dissertation and one post-doc was trained in model-data comparison. Combinedwithsimilar outcomes among the other project partners this constitutes a lasting contribution to interdisciplinary STEM training and research capacity. The resulting proxy compilations and model output which are or will all be publiclyavailable through archives also constitute lasting data resources for the broader community.


